The paper deals with constructing spanners for wireless networks, which is a topic in the field of networked systems and communication (cs.NI). The algorithm presented involves graph theory and optimization techniques, which are common in the subfield of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The use of localized techniques and the focus on communication rounds suggests a connection to distributed computing (cs.DC). The construction of a planar spanner suggests a connection to computational geometry (cs.CG). Finally, the use of minimum spanning trees and Delaunay triangulations suggests a connection to discrete mathematics (cs.DM).
